    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-05-06T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-05-06T17:00:00-05:00" n="95"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d95">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5531/555: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Belgium</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-06T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 6, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>25. Your 48, May 4, 3 p.m. Automobile Manufacturers Association which has been in
                    touch with various companies has informed the Department that it has no
                    objection to the proposals outlined in your telegram.</p>
                <p>The proposed license tax of 20 percent of the duty on 4-cylinder passenger cars
                    is of practically no interest to us. However, if this were extended to items
                    which are of interest and on which duty concessions have been made, we would of
                    course have objection since the tax would tend to offset the advantages gained
                    from the concession.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
